# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1892-washington-senators-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1891-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1891 throughout the world.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1891-washington-statesmen-season] The **1891 Washington Statesmen** baseball team finished the season with a 44–91 record in the American Association in their first season.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1891-washington-statesmen-season] After the season, the AA disbanded and the Washington club, renamed the "Senators," joined the National League.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-baltimore-orioles-season] The **1892 Baltimore Orioles season** was the first season that the professional baseball team known as the Baltimore Orioles competed in the National League, following the demise of the American Association.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-baltimore-orioles-season] In a split season schedule, the Orioles finished last in the first half of the season and 10th in the second half.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-baltimore-orioles-season] Overall, the team had a record of 46–101, worst in the 12-team National League.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-baltimore-orioles-season] The 19th-century Orioles franchise is not the Baltimore Orioles franchise that has competed in the American League since 1954.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-boston-beaneaters-season] The **1892 Boston Beaneaters season** was the 22nd season of the franchise.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-boston-beaneaters-season] The Beaneaters won their second straight and fifth overall National League pennant.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-boston-beaneaters-season] In the league's first split season, the Beaneaters finished first in the first half, and three games behind the Cleveland Spiders in the second half.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-boston-beaneaters-season] After the season, the two teams played a "World's Championship Series", which the Beaneaters won, five games to none (with one tie).
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-boston-beaneaters-season] The National League did not play another split season until 1981.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-boston-beaneaters-season] The Boston Beaneaters, first-half champions, played the second-half champion Cleveland Spiders in a best-of-nine postseason series.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-boston-beaneaters-season] After a 0–0 tie in the opener, called on account of darkness after 11 innings, Boston defeated Cleveland five games in a row for a sweep.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-boston-beaneaters-season] Hall of Famer Hugh Duffy batted .462 with nine runs batted in and six extra-base hits including a home run.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-brooklyn-grooms-season] The **1892 Brooklyn Grooms season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-brooklyn-grooms-season] The team finished the first half of the split season in second place, just 2.5 games behind the Boston Beaneaters.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-brooklyn-grooms-season] However, they faded in the second half, finishing 9.5 games behind the second-half champion Cleveland Spiders and missing out on the postseason playoff.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-brooklyn-grooms-season] Their combined record was 95–59, third best overall in the league.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-brooklyn-grooms-season] The season was a tragic one, as outfielder Hub Collins left a game on May 14 because he was feeling ill.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-brooklyn-grooms-season] A week later he was dead, the victim of typhoid fever.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-brooklyn-grooms-season] The team put on a benefit game to raise money for his widow on May 29.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-brooklyn-grooms-season] One bright spot, however, was first baseman Dan Brouthers, who won the batting title with a .335 batting average.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-chicago-colts-season] The **1892 Chicago Colts season** was the 21st season of the Chicago Colts franchise, their 17th in the National League and the second at South Side Park.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-chicago-colts-season] In a split season schedule, the Colts finished eighth in the first half of the season and seventh in the second half.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-chicago-colts-season] Overall, the team had a record of 70–76, seventh-best in the 12-team National League.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-cincinnati-reds-season] The **1892 Cincinnati Reds season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-cincinnati-reds-season] The National League expanded to 12 teams in 1892, and it was announced that the season would be split into two halves, with the winners of each half meeting in a "World's Championship Series".
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds finished with a combined record of 82–68, fifth-best in the National League, finishing in fourth place in the first half and in eighth place in the second half.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-cincinnati-reds-season] After a horrible 1891 season in which the Reds finished in a virtual tie for last place with a 56–81 record, the team fired manager Tom Loftus and replaced him with first baseman Charles Comiskey.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-cincinnati-reds-season] Comiskey had previously been the player-manager of the St.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-cincinnati-reds-season] Louis Browns of the American Association from 1883 to 1889, leading the team to four straight pennants from 1885 to 1888.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-cincinnati-reds-season] He then was a player-manager with the Chicago Pirates of the Players' League in 1890, leading them to a fourth-place finish, followed by a return to the Browns in 1891, where he led them to a second-place finish with a record of 86–52.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds acquired outfielder Tip O'Neill during the off-season, as he spent the 1891 season with Comiskey with the Browns, hitting .323 with ten homers and 95 RBI for the club.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-cincinnati-reds-season] O'Neill's best season was in 1887 with the Browns, when he hit .435, with 225 hits, 167 runs, 52 doubles, nineteen triples, fourteen home runs and 123 RBI, all of which led the American Association.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-cincinnati-reds-season] Catcher Morgan Murphy was picked by from the Boston Reds of the AA.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-cincinnati-reds-season] Murphy hit .216 with four homers and 54 RBI in 106 games.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-cincinnati-reds-season] Another catcher, Farmer Vaughn, was signed after he split the 1891 season between the Cincinnati Kelly's Killers and Milwaukee Brewers of the AA.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-cincinnati-reds-season] Vaughn hit .285 with a homer and 23 RBI between the two clubs.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-cincinnati-reds-season] Pitcher Ice Box Chamberlain also signed with the Reds after posting a 22–23 record with a 4.22 with the Philadelphia Athletics of the AA.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-cincinnati-reds-season] Bug Holliday once again was the Reds offensive leader, hitting .294 with a team high thirteen home runs and 91 RBI.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-cincinnati-reds-season] Bid McPhee hit .274 with four homers and 60 RBI and 44 stolen bases, while Germany Smith hit .243 with eight homers and 63 RBI.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-cincinnati-reds-season] On the mound, Tony Mullane led the staff with a 21–13 record and a 2.59 ERA, while Chamberlain had a 19–23 record with a 3.39 ERA in a team high 49 starts.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-cincinnati-reds-season] In the second half, the Reds were mediocre, as they finished in eighth place with a 38–37 record, 14½ games behind the Cleveland Spiders.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-cincinnati-reds-season] They finished the season with a combined record of 82–68, which marked a big improvement over the previous year.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-washington-senators-season] The **1892 Washington Senators season** was a season in American professional baseball.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-washington-senators-season] The team, which had played in the now-defunct American Association in 1891 as the **Washington Statesmen**, was purchased by J.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-washington-senators-season] Earl Wagner and moved to the National League for the 1892 season.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-washington-senators-season] In a split season schedule, the Senators finished seventh in the first half of the season and last in the second half.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-washington-senators-season] Overall, the team had a record of 58–93, 10th-best in the 12-team National League.
[src:1892-washington-senators-season/1892-washington-senators-season] The Senators held spring training in Savannah, Georgia at Bolton Street Park.
